True.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 is bounded, it must contain a convergent subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n_{k}})\to L$
\end_inset

 by Bolzano-Weierstrass.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 does not converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, by definition, there must exist 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{n}-L|\geq\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Define a new subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{N})$
\end_inset

, by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{N}$
\end_inset

 be the term 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{n})$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{n}-L|\geq\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{N})$
\end_inset

 is bounded and therefore has a convergent subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{N_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 But it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $(y_{N_{k}})$
\end_inset

 does not converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, since for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $|y_{N_{k}}-L|\geq\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
