\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Proof
Suppose the NIP is true, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty set of real numbers that is bounded above.
 We want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has a least upper bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is bounded above, there is some number 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $s\leq M_{1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{1}\in S$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and consider the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=[s_{1},M_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
 Bisect the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}=[s,M]$
\end_inset

 and choose a closed half-interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}\subseteq I_{1}$
\end_inset

 by letting 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the right half-interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\frac{s_{1}+M_{1}}{2},M_{1}]$
\end_inset

 if there is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in[\frac{s+M}{2},M_{1}]$
\end_inset

 and letting 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the left half-interval otherwise.
 (If neither is possible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is empty, a contradiction.) Repeat this process, at each stage choosing
 the closed half-interval 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}\subseteq I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 to be the right half-interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\frac{s_{k-1}+M_{k-1}}{2},M_{k-1}]$
\end_inset

 if the right half-interval contains an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and the left half-interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[s_{k-1},\frac{s_{k-1}+M_{k-1}}{2}]$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 At each stage, one of the halves must contain an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, otherwise there were no elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 at the previous stage.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{1}\supseteq I_{2}\supseteq I_{3}\supseteq\dots
\]

\end_inset

is a nested sequence of closed, bounded intervals, so there exists an element
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{k=1}^{\infty}I_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sup S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To prove this, note that the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

 is half the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{1}$
\end_inset

 was 
\begin_inset Formula $M-s$
\end_inset

, so the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{k}|$
\end_inset

, is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|I_{k}|=\frac{M-s}{2^{k-1}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since we are assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/2^{n})\to0$
\end_inset

, the Algebraic Limit Theorem tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $|I_{k}|=(M-s)(\frac{1}{2^{k-1}})\to0$
\end_inset

 as well.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcap_{k=1}^{\infty}I_{k}=\{x\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now, suppose for contradiction that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x<s$
\end_inset

.
 Then it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $s>M_{k}$
\end_inset

, which is impossible because we chose 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{k}$
\end_inset

 to be an upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be another upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose for contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<x$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a lower bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{k}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<s_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, which is impossible since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the least upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, and the Axiom of Completeness is proven.
\end_layout

